Business clients might prefer clarity with a touch of creativity ("Content Compass" sounds professional enough for a business context yet interesting). We avoid anything too slangy or too academic.

By using these branded names across brochures, the website, and sales calls, Lingua Ink reinforces its brand at every step. Instead of saying "I'll do an edit and marketing plan for you," we can say "We recommend our Manuscript Makeover followed by a Launchpad Marketing package to give your book its best start." This not only sounds more polished and productized, but also helps clients remember and talk about our services to others. Each name carries connotations that support our values - improvement, guidance, empowerment - and together they build a narrative that working with Lingua Ink is an engaging, elevating experience.

## 8\. Templates & Deliverables

Consistency in branding must extend to every deliverable - from an email signature to a PowerPoint presentation. In this section, we outline guidelines and examples for key templates and collateral. These ensure that whether someone receives an email from us, a business card, or sees our slides at a workshop, the look and feel scream "Lingua Ink."

**Email Signature:** Every team member should use a standardized, branded email signature for professional correspondence. Keep it **simple, informative, and on-brand**: - Use our **brand fonts** if possible (often email clients default to system fonts, so a safe choice is a common font like Georgia or Arial in lieu of Bitter/Domine). Use charcoal (#484C53) for text. - Include Name, Title, and Company: - e.g., **Maya Bairey** | Founder & Creative Director, Lingua Ink Books & Media. - Contact info in a single line or two lines: phone, email, website. For example: "✉ <info@linguaink.com> • ☏ (503) 847-9860 • 🌐 <www.linguaink.com>". Use symbols or icons sparingly for visual interest (email, phone, globe as shown) - but ensure they render well in email. - Add the Lingua Ink logo (small) or wordmark: ideally a 100px tall image of our logo placed below or beside the text. Often, placing a small logo image aligned to the right works, or at the bottom as a sign-off. Make sure the image is not too large (keep file size small, and provide ALT text like "Lingua Ink Books logo"). - Use the accent color as a highlight: for example, hyperlink the website in brick red, or use the red for your name or a separator line. But don't overdo color in signatures (too many colors can trigger spam filters or look unprofessional). - **Example Signature:**

_Best regards,_&lt;br&gt; **Maya Bairey**&lt;br&gt; Founder & Creative Director, **Lingua Ink**&lt;br&gt; <info@linguaink.com> | (503) 847-9860 | <www.linguaink.com&lt;br>&gt; Lingua Ink Books logo small  

(In practice, the logo would appear aligned with the text. All text might be one shade of charcoal, with "Lingua Ink" possibly in the red or bolded.) This format ensures every email sent reinforces our brand identity and provides key info at a glance. It's professional but not fussy.

**Business Cards:** Lingua Ink business cards should reflect the unified brand, covering both Books and Media. Opt for a **clean, double-sided design**: - **Front:** Display the Lingua Ink logo prominently. Given our logo has an icon and text, we can center the inkpot icon with "Lingua Ink" logotype. Perhaps include the tagline or descriptor: e.g., "Books • Media" under the logo to denote both arms (small caps or a neat font). Use the primary dark or the accent color for background depending on aesthetic: a popular choice is a white card with logo in full color; or a charcoal background with the logo in white for a bold look. Ensure logo is crisp (vector). - **Back:** List individual's name, title, and contact details. Use Bitter for name (maybe in Lingua red to stand out), and Domine for contact info. For example:

**Maya Bairey**&lt;br&gt; Founder & Creative Director&lt;br&gt; 10350 N Vancouver Way, Suite 351B&lt;br&gt; Portland, OR 97217&lt;br&gt; (503) 847-9860 | <maya@linguaink.com>&lt;br&gt; <www.linguaink.com>

Use subtle graphic elements: maybe a faint ink splash watermark in one corner (in a 10% tint of red or gray) to tie in the brand motif without overwhelming. The accent red can be used as small pops - e.g., maybe a vertical red stripe or a thin border line, or simply the name in red. Keep plenty of white (or light gray) space for an uncluttered look. Standard card size, high-quality matte stock.

- **Printing & Finish:** Consider using a matte finish with possibly a spot gloss on the logo (if budget allows for a premium feel). Rounded corners are optional but can modernize the look; ensure consistency if chosen (rounded corners might complement the friendly approachable vibe). The card should feel sturdy to signal quality.

**Letterhead & Document Template:** For formal documents (proposals, contracts, letters), prepare a Word template with our branding: - **Header:** Place the Lingua Ink logo at top (left or centered). Could be a small logo icon with "Lingua Ink Books & Media" text. If the document is primarily for one arm, you can use that logo variant (e.g., proposals for consulting might use "Lingua Ink Media" wordmark in header). - Possibly include company address and website in the header (right-aligned in smaller font). - **Footer:** Use a footer for page number and perhaps a repeat of website or a tagline. For example, a subtle line and then "www.linguaink.com" or "Amplifying Authentic Voices - in Publishing & Media" in 8pt Domine italic. - Ensure the default styles in the template use our typography: Headings in Bitter (color #484C53 or accent color if appropriate), body in Domine (charcoal). Set up H1, H2 etc., consistent with the Style Bible's hierarchy. Maybe H1 16pt Bitter Bold, H2 14pt Bitter, Body 11pt Domine. - **Margins** generous (1" all around or 0.75" at least) to echo our love of whitespace. - Use the accent color for small elements: table header backgrounds, or bolded subheadings, or the bullets in lists could be red dashes or ink-drop shaped glyphs if fancy. Keep it professional; no rainbow of colors, just the red with black/gray. - This letterhead template will be used for proposals, SOWs, etc., so make sure it's not heavy on ink (white background for main body). The logo should not dominate the page - maybe 1" wide in header.

**Proposal / Slide Deck Template:** Lingua Ink Media often will pitch services or present workshops, so a PowerPoint/Google Slides template is key. We ensure the slides carry our brand seamlessly[\[71\]](file://file-HAideRvS3MuwvTBnDaQXD5#:~:text=Presentation%20Slide%20Deck%20Template%3A%20,when%20you%20speak%20or%20teach): - **Cover Slide:** Use a branded cover layout: perhaps a solid background in charcoal or white. If charcoal background, put the logo and presentation title in white. If white background, use charcoal text. Possibly include an image strip if relevant (for a workshop, maybe a faint full-slide background image like a collage of book covers or a writing concept, overlaid with our brand color filter to not distract). Title in Bitter, large. Subtitle or event info in Domine. Include Lingua Ink logo and perhaps the tagline or speaker name. - **Inside Slides:** Maintain a clean layout with plenty of whitespace for readability. - Master fonts: Bitter for slide titles (maybe 32pt), Domine for body (min 18pt for visibility). Use our charcoal for most text. Use accent red sparingly for emphasis or certain headings/shapes. - **Color scheme:** predominately white background with black text is safest for printing and projecting. Use accent color for section headers or important bullets. For example, section divider slides might have a red background with white text to signal a new section (but ensure the red is not too intense for an entire slide people stare at - possibly use red for a banner or shape instead). - **Bullets and visuals:** Use simple bullets (solid circles or en dashes in charcoal or red). Align with our typography hierarchy - e.g., first-level bullet 18pt Domine, second-level 16pt Domine. - Incorporate small graphic elements: perhaps a thin line in footer or header in accent color, or use the ink splash motif in the corner of slides lightly. Keep any such element subtle (low opacity or small size) so it doesn't interfere with content. - **Footer on slides:** probably include the Lingua Ink logo or name and page number. A common approach: left footer: "Lingua Ink Media" text, right footer: page number. Use Domine 10pt. - **Example Slide Styles:** - Title Slide: "Content Marketing 101 for Authors" - white background, Lingua Ink logo top-right, title in Bitter Red center-left, small byline "Maya Bairey, Lingua Ink Media Workshop" below in charcoal Domine. - Content Slide: White background, black heading in Bitter 28pt, body text bullets in black Domine 20pt. Maybe a brick red line under heading or a brick red bullet symbol for each bullet to tie brand color in. Images: if inserting screenshots or graphics, use a consistent style (all screenshots have same browser frame if needed, all photos have similar rounded corners or drop shadow style, etc.). - Section Divider: A slide that just says "Q&A" or "Step 2: Strategy" - could invert colors: charcoal background, white text Bitter, and maybe the inkpot icon ghosted big in the background.

All these ensure that when someone sees our deck, it's identifiable as ours. The template file (.pptx or Google Slides) should be easily accessible; we might include a note in the style guide on where to find the latest template file[\[72\]](file://file-HAideRvS3MuwvTBnDaQXD5#:~:text=Templates%20,you%20always%20use%20the%20latest).

**Other Documents & Deliverables:** - **Branded Word Proposal:** As touched on, any proposal PDF or doc we send should use the letterhead template. We might also create a designed PDF proposal format for higher impact: e.g., a 4-5 page mini deck style, exported as PDF, with branded cover, etc. But the content structure remains: cover with project name and our branding, then content in brand fonts/colors. Including client's logo alongside ours on cover can personalize it. - **Author Handbook / Guides:** If we provide an author handbook or course PDF (like the Self-Pub Cheat Sheet), ensure the design follows our style. For example, the cheat sheet PDF could have chapter headings in Bitter red, body text in Domine, with callout boxes in light gray with a red border for tips. Use our logo on the cover page and in footers. Maintain at least 12pt font for older readers and plenty of contrast. - **Email Newsletter Template:** Our Mailchimp or email marketing template should also reflect branding: use our header/logo at top, accent-colored buttons, and Bitter/Domine web-safe alternatives in the design. Keep it mobile-responsive. Perhaps a red call-to-action button ("Read More on our Blog") to align with site style.

- **Business Proposal Slides vs. Literary Pitch Decks:** If we ever pitch to investors or partners, adapt tone accordingly but keep visuals branded. Possibly have a variant of the template emphasizing Lingua Ink Media's professional side (more charcoal, less whimsical elements). Conversely, if creating a rights catalog or pitch for books, you might lean into a more literary look (maybe incorporate subtle background of pages). But these are refinements; core branding remains consistent.
- **Social Media Graphics:** Templates for quote posts or announcements (e.g., a Canva template where we plug in a quote from an author or a tip) should be set up with our fonts and colors. For instance, an Instagram quote template: white background, a quotation mark graphic in light gray, text in charcoal Bitter italic, author name in red Domine below, and a small Lingua Ink logo in a corner. This way even individual social posts are on-brand (no random colors or fonts used on the fly).

By establishing these templates and adhering to them, we ensure every touchpoint looks polished and "on the same team." It saves time (no reinventing layouts each time) and bolsters brand recognition (someone reading a Lingua Ink proposal or seeing our workshop slides will immediately note the familiar style). Importantly, the **templates are living documents** - the Style Bible should note where to find or how to update them as needed (for example, keeping the proposal template updated with current address, etc.)[\[73\]](file://file-HAideRvS3MuwvTBnDaQXD5#:~:text=9.%20Client,Process%20Docs).

Overall, these guidelines will help maintain a seamless visual and tonal continuity from digital screens to printed page. As Lingua Ink grows, new collateral (like merchandise, event banners, etc.) can be designed by drawing on these same principles - ensuring that whether it's a bookmark giveaway or a course certificate, it feels undeniably Lingua Ink: modern, thoughtful, and unified.
